explanation:
Needed symbols and why they matter for a dead-code (MISRA) analysis of OS_BinSemCreate:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER: Macro that may perform an early return or other side-effects; must know if it can make subsequent code unreachable (thus affecting dead-code determination).
- OS_CHECK_APINAME: Same as above for sem_name; may validate/name-check and possibly return or alter control flow.
- OS_ObjectIdAllocateNew: The enclosing if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS) depends on this function's return behavior; if it always fails/succeeds or has side effects, that changes whether the inner block is dead.
- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: The object type argument passed to allocation can change allocation behavior (selector/compile-time configuration) and therefore affect reachability of the inner block.
- OS_object_token_t: Type of token; needed to know whether passing &token to other routines has side effects (e.g., initialization) that matter to code usefulness.
- osal_id_t: Type of sem_id; required to know whether OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew writes to it (side effect) and thus whether earlier operations are necessary.
- OS_bin_sem_internal_record_t: Type of binsem (structure); needed to see whether OS_OBJECT_INIT/OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET manipulate fields that are later read (so not dead).
- OS_bin_sem_table: The global table accessed by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; required to determine whether obtaining binsem is necessary for later behavior.
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro/function that obtains the table entry; its semantics/side effects determine whether the assignment to binsem is required or dead.
- OS_OBJECT_INIT: Macro/function that resets/saves the object name; must know if it has side effects relied on later (e.g., used by Impl or finalize) so it is not removable.
- OS_BinSemCreate_Impl: The OS-specific create implementation is called and (per comment) reads the table; its behavior determines if prior initialization (OS_OBJECT_INIT, table fetch) is actually used — critical to deciding if those statements are dead.
- OS_ObjectIdFinalizeNew: Finalization can overwrite return_code, set *sem_id, perform cleanup or notifications; must know whether it makes prior assignments or the Impl call redundant.
- OS_SUCCESS: The constant used in the conditional; needed to reason about the if-test and whether branches are taken under given configurations.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Appears in the static call graph (likely used by the macros/impls); its behavior could be involved in table indexing and side effects affecting whether table access is necessary.
- OS_ObjectIdGlobalFromToken: Likewise used by macros/utility code called here; may affect global object state and thus whether earlier operations are needed.
- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: These unit-test stub hooks appear in the static call graph (macros/instrumentation). Their presence can alter control flow or replace function returns in test builds; to assess dead code in both production and test configurations you need to know whether these hooks can make parts of this function effectively dead.

In short: to decide whether any statements in OS_BinSemCreate are dead (i.e., removable without changing program behavior) one must know the precise semantics, side-effects, and potential early returns of the parameter-check macros, the allocation/finalize routines, the table access/init macros, the OS-specific Impl, and the relevant types/constants and test-stub hooks that can change control flow or side effects.
